== SPI slave (minimal)

Four-wire SPI slave in mode 0 with a small opcode set --- JEDEC ID
(0x9F), RDSR (0x05), Normal Read (0x03), Fast Read (0x0B), Write
Enable (0x06), Write Disable (0x04), Page Program (0x02), Quad
Output Read (0x6B), and SFDP Read (0x5A) --- backed by a 16-byte page buffer plus a
128-byte SFDP parameter ROM. At the end of every frame (CS
rising edge) the module prints one UART line
`op=<hh> bytes=<K> mosi_crc=<8hex>\r\n` through the reused `uart_tx`
from the UART chapter.

The headline product feature this slave must support is
high-throughput streaming reads. The MP135 host issues 0x0B (Fast
Read, single-lane) and 0x6B (Quad Output Read) frames that span
the full 24-bit address space at SCLK rates up to 102 MHz (chip
maximum: quadspi_ker_ck / 2 = 204 MHz / 2). To make the integrity
of those reads testable end-to-end without a real flash array
behind the slave, the read data is a deterministic incrementing
pattern: byte at flash address A returns A[7:0]. The host can
therefore stream a megabyte and assert byte K of the response
equals (start_addr + K) mod 256, catching any framing, CDC, or
nibble-pairing glitch byte-by-byte. The 16-byte page buffer is
retained for Page Program (0x02) and Quad Page Program (0x32)
verification only --- read opcodes ignore it and stream the
pattern instead.

The four SPI data pins are exposed as an `inout [3:0] io` port so the
FPGA can drive all four lines during the 0x6B data phase and leave
them Hi-Z otherwise. MOSI (single-lane) is `io[0]` sampled as an
input; MISO (single-lane) is `io[1]` driven as an output when a
single-lane opcode is in its response window.

<<qspi.v>>=
module qspi (
      input        clk,
      input        cs_n,
      input        sclk,
      inout  [3:0] io,
      output       tx
   );
   <<SPI: shift engine>>
   <<SPI: quad output engine>>
   <<SPI: quad input engine>>
   <<SPI: IO drivers>>
   <<SPI: MOSI CRC-32>>
   <<SPI: page buffer and WEL>>
   <<SPI: end-of-frame latch>>
   <<SPI: UART printer FSM>>
   <<SPI: uart_tx instance>>
endmodule
@

Capture is clocked directly on `sclk` with no fclk synchroniser
chain on the data path. A two-flop sync would limit usable SCLK to
a fraction of `clk` (12 MHz); flops driven directly off `sclk`
reach the iCE40 HX1K's input-flop fmax (>250 MHz), well past the
STM32MP135's SDR ceiling.

The clock-domain partition:

- All capture state (`bit_cnt`, `shift_in`, `byte_cnt`, `opcode`,
  `addr_low`, RAM writes, CRC, `qin_phase`, `nibble_buf`,
  `quad_in_cnt`) is clocked on `posedge sclk` with `cs_async_rst`
  as an asynchronous clear so the first frame after CS-fall starts
  cleanly. Raw `cs_n` falling releases `cs_async_rst` immediately
  so the sclk-domain flops are ready before the first SCLK edge.
  On CS rise, `cs_async_rst` is reasserted from the *output* of
  `cs_s_d` (the second-stage delayed mirror of `cs_s`), not
  directly from `cs_n`. This keeps the asynchronous clear strictly
  later than the synchronous snapshot trigger (`cs_rise_pulse`,
  which fires one fclk earlier), so the snapshot always captures
  the pre-clear value of the source registers.
- Single-lane response data is precomputed on `posedge sclk`, then
  presented by a fabric `negedge sclk` register named `io_pad_out`.
  Quad responses likewise precompute their next pad value on
  `posedge sclk`, then capture `io_pad_src` into `io_pad_out`. The
  `SB_IO` cells are unregistered bidirectional pads.
- There is no flash-data backing store: read responses come
  from the `data_byte` pattern counter described in the
  streaming-pattern section below. Page Program (0x02) and Quad
  Page Program (0x32) frames still run end-to-end (opcode +
  address + WEL gating + byte count + CRC), but the data they
  carry is not written into any storage --- the printer's
  per-frame log line is the observable outcome.
- WEL update happens in the fclk domain on the cs-rise pulse.
- Two fclk-domain consumers tap the `cs_sync` chain: the
  `cs_rise_pulse` (consumed by the WEL update and the UART printer
  FSM) and the `cs_async_rst` async-reset for the sclk domain,
  which is one further fclk-flop downstream of `cs_s`. By the
  time `cs_rise_pulse` fires, the sclk-domain registers have
  been quiescent for at least one fclk cycle (no more sclk edges
  arrive until the next CS-fall), and the snapshot block has had
  one fclk cycle to copy their values into the fclk-domain
  `frame_op` / `frame_cnt` / `frame_crc_raw` registers before
  `cs_async_rst` rises and clears the source flops.

@

The shift engine lives entirely in the `sclk` domain. Its
responsibilities split into five named pieces: capture-state
declarations, the boundary-derived combinational signals, the
synchronous `posedge sclk` process, the WEL CDC flop, and the
RAM-port wiring.

<<SPI: shift engine>>=
<<SPI: shift engine state>>
<<SPI: shift engine boundary signals>>
<<SPI: shift engine sclk process>>
<<SPI: shift engine WEL synchroniser>>
<<SPI: shift engine RAM ports>>
<<SPI: SFDP ROM>>
@

The capture state is split between a wide `byte_cnt` that the
printer displays as the `bytes=` field and a narrower saturating
`phase_cnt` (0..7) that drives every per-byte control decision in
the FSM. Keeping the wide comparator out of the per-arm logic
shortens the sclk-domain critical path; sixteen bits of `byte_cnt`
are still wide enough for the printer's modulo-100 display.
`addr_low` indexes the 16-byte page buffer (still used by 0x02
and 0x32 page-program writes). `data_byte` is the 8-bit pattern
counter for 0x03 / 0x0B single-lane response data and the captured
address-low seed for 0x6B. The quad-output path copies that seed
into `quad_data_byte` on the quad start boundary, then owns its own
upper/lower nibble cadence and once-per-byte increment for the rest
of the 0x6B data phase.
`quad_in_cnt`,
`nibble_buf`, and `qin_phase` are state owned by the 0x32 quad
page-program data phase but declared here because the same
`always @(posedge sclk)` block writes them.

<<SPI: shift engine state>>=
reg [2:0]  bit_cnt;
reg [6:0]  shift_in;
reg [7:0]  shift_out;
reg [7:0]  opcode;
reg [2:0]  phase_cnt;
reg [15:0] byte_cnt;
reg [3:0]  addr_low;
reg [7:0]  data_byte;
reg [19:0] quad_in_cnt;
reg [3:0]  nibble_buf;
reg        qin_phase;
reg [6:0]  sfdp_idx;

initial begin
   bit_cnt     = 0;
   shift_in    = 0;
   shift_out   = 0;
   opcode      = 0;
   phase_cnt   = 0;
   byte_cnt    = 0;
   addr_low    = 0;
   data_byte   = 0;
   quad_in_cnt = 0;
   nibble_buf  = 0;
   qin_phase   = 0;
   sfdp_idx    = 0;
end
@

`byte_captured` is the value of the byte that has just finished
shifting in: bits 6..0 already in `shift_in` plus the bit currently
arriving on `io[0]`. `new_low` is its bottom nibble, used by
opcodes that latch the address-low. `byte_done` strobes for one
sclk on each byte boundary. `quad_in_phase` is high during the
0x32 data phase only.

<<SPI: shift engine boundary signals>>=
wire [7:0] byte_captured = {shift_in[6:0], io_d_in[0]};
wire [3:0] new_low       = byte_captured[3:0];
wire       byte_done     = (bit_cnt == 3'd7);
wire       quad_in_phase = (opcode == 8'h32) && (phase_cnt >= 3'd4);
@

The `posedge sclk` process gates everything off the
`cs_async_rst` asynchronous clear so each frame starts from a
clean slate the moment CS falls; while CS is high any spurious
sclk edges are masked by the held reset. The body splits into a reset arm and a per-rise
arm; the per-rise arm itself decomposes into the byte-rate shift
input, the default left-shift of `shift_out` between byte loads,
the inferred-RAM write statement, the 0x32 quad-input data phase,
the 0x6B quad-output precompute, and the byte-boundary opcode
dispatch.

<<SPI: shift engine sclk process>>=
always @(posedge sclk or posedge cs_async_rst) begin
   if (cs_async_rst) begin
      <<SPI: shift engine reset>>
   end else begin
      <<SPI: shift in and bit counter>>
      <<SPI: shift out default>>
      <<SPI: RAM write at boundaries>>
      <<SPI: quad input data phase>>
      <<SPI: quad output nibble precompute>>
      <<SPI: single-lane data-phase increment>>
      <<SPI: byte boundary actions>>
   end
end
@

The single-lane reads (0x03 and 0x0B) emit one pattern byte per
single-lane SCLK byte. The increment is pulled out of the
opcode-dispatch case-chain into its own chunk so the
`data_byte` flop is fed by a shallow LUT rather than by a deep
priority encoder threading through every dispatch arm. The
preload at the phase-3 boundary (capturing the address LSB,
optionally plus 1 for 0x03's same-boundary first response byte)
remains in the dispatch chunk because it is mutually exclusive
with the data-phase increment: the increment fires only at
phase counts STRICTLY past the preload phase.

<<SPI: single-lane data-phase increment>>=
if (byte_done && (   (opcode == 8'h03 && phase_cnt >  3'd3)
                  || (opcode == 8'h0B && phase_cnt >= 3'd4)))
   data_byte <= data_byte + 8'd1;
@

For 0x6B Quad Output Read the slave emits each logical byte upper
nibble then lower nibble, so a master that pairs the launched nibbles
in pad-visible order captures the incrementing byte pattern. The
stream emits one pattern byte every two sclk rises (one rise per
nibble).
Opcode 0x6C uses the same framing but emits the diagnostic one-hot nibble stream
1,2,4,8,... so the STM32 capture can distinguish lane loss from
nibble phase slip. Opcode 0x6D uses the same framing again but
emits the nibble diagnostic sequence 0,6,0,7,0,8,0,9,0,a,0,b,0,c,0,d,...
to separate byte-index/FIFO-boundary faults from value-transition
faults. Opcode 0x6E emits 00,11,22,...,ff repeatedly so each quad
nibble value is held for both sample edges in one byte. Opcode 0x6F
emits the continuous nibble ramp 0,1,2,...,f,0,... to isolate
nibble-to-nibble transition timing from byte-boundary effects. The
post-dummy byte boundary explicitly starts the quad stream: the posedge precompute
captures the first quad byte and prepares its first pad nibble before
the first data-phase negedge. For 0x6B, that first pad nibble is the
seed upper nibble; the following data-phase rises emit the seed lower
nibble, advance the byte, then emit the next byte's upper nibble.
Diagnostics keep their existing nibble order. A quad-owned
`quad_active` latch owns the ongoing data-phase qualifier after
the one-cycle start boundary. For the byte-oriented quad responses, `quad_hi_next` tracks the
upper/lower cadence instead of deriving it from `bit_cnt[0]`,
keeping the quad output phase independent of the single-lane
shift counter and shared `data_byte` cadence.

<<SPI: quad output nibble precompute>>=
if (quad_start) begin
   quad_active       <= 1'b1;
   quad_data_drive_r <= 1'b1;
   if (opcode == 8'h6C) begin
      quad_next_nibble  <= quad_onehot(2'd0);
      quad_diag_idx     <= 4'd1;
      quad_data_byte    <= 8'h00;
   end else if (opcode == 8'h6D) begin
      quad_next_nibble  <= 4'h0;
      quad_diag_idx     <= 4'd1;
   end else if (opcode == 8'h6E) begin
      quad_next_nibble  <= 4'h0;
      quad_diag_idx     <= 4'd0;
      quad_data_byte    <= 8'h00;
   end else if (opcode == 8'h6F) begin
      quad_next_nibble  <= 4'h0;
      quad_diag_idx     <= 4'd0;
      quad_data_byte    <= 8'h00;
   end else begin
      quad_next_nibble  <= quad_data_byte_seed[7:4];
      quad_diag_idx     <= 4'd0;
      quad_data_byte    <= quad_data_byte_seed;
   end
   quad_hi_next      <= 1'b0;
end else if (quad_data) begin
   quad_data_drive_r <= 1'b1;
   if (opcode == 8'h6C) begin
      quad_next_nibble <= quad_onehot(quad_diag_idx[1:0]);
      quad_diag_idx    <= quad_diag_idx + 4'd1;
   end else if (opcode == 8'h6D) begin
      quad_next_nibble <= quad_diag6d_nibble;
      quad_diag_idx    <= quad_diag_idx + 4'd1;
   end else if (opcode == 8'h6F) begin
      quad_next_nibble <= quad_next_nibble + 4'd1;
   end else if (opcode == 8'h6B) begin
      if (quad_hi_next) begin
         quad_next_nibble <= quad_data_byte_inc[7:4];
         quad_data_byte   <= quad_data_byte_inc;
         quad_hi_next     <= 1'b0;
      end else begin
         quad_next_nibble <= quad_data_byte[3:0];
         quad_hi_next     <= 1'b1;
      end
   end else begin
      if (quad_hi_next) begin
         if (opcode == 8'h6E) begin
            quad_next_nibble <= quad_hold_byte_inc[7:4];
            quad_data_byte   <= quad_hold_byte_inc;
         end else begin
            quad_next_nibble <= quad_data_byte_inc[7:4];
            quad_data_byte   <= quad_data_byte_inc;
         end
         quad_hi_next     <= 1'b0;
      end else begin
         quad_next_nibble <= quad_data_byte[3:0];
         quad_hi_next     <= 1'b1;
      end
   end
end else begin
   quad_active       <= 1'b0;
   quad_data_drive_r <= 1'b0;
   quad_hi_next      <= 1'b0;
   quad_diag_idx     <= 4'd0;
end
@

<<SPI: shift engine reset>>=
bit_cnt     <= 0;
phase_cnt   <= 0;
byte_cnt    <= 0;
opcode      <= 0;
shift_in    <= 0;
shift_out   <= 0;
addr_low    <= 0;
data_byte   <= 0;
qin_phase   <= 0;
quad_in_cnt <= 0;
nibble_buf  <= 0;
sfdp_idx    <= 0;
quad_active       <= 0;
quad_next_nibble  <= 0;
quad_data_byte    <= 0;
quad_data_drive_r <= 0;
quad_hi_next      <= 0;
quad_diag_idx     <= 0;
@

The single-lane MOSI bit arrives on `io[0]`. We append it to the
running shift register and increment the bit counter; when
`bit_cnt` wraps from 7 to 0 the byte-boundary arm picks up.

<<SPI: shift in and bit counter>>=
shift_in <= {shift_in[5:0], io_d_in[0]};
bit_cnt  <= bit_cnt + 3'd1;
@

Between byte loads, `shift_out` left-shifts every cycle so the
negedge presenter sees the correct outgoing bit on `shift_out[7]`.
A boundary load in the dispatch chunk below overrides this default
on the same cycle.

<<SPI: shift out default>>=
shift_out <= {shift_out[6:0], 1'b0};
@

With the streaming pattern source replacing the page buffer as
the read data source, there is no observable consumer of write
data: the response-data path is `data_byte`, not `ram`. The
RAM-write statement is therefore intentionally empty in the
shift-engine process. WEL gating, address handling, and the
quad-input nibble pairing for 0x32 still run as before --- only
the storage step has been elided. The named chunk is kept so
the shift-engine process structure remains literate; tangling
emits no Verilog.

<<SPI: RAM write at boundaries>>=
@

For 0x32 Quad Page Program the master drives all four IO pins
during the data phase; the FPGA samples `io[3:0]` on every sclk
rise and pairs two rises into one byte. `qin_phase` toggles per
rise: phase 0 latches the upper nibble into `nibble_buf`, phase 1
delivers the lower nibble (the actual write happens through the
shared RAM-write statement above) and advances both the page
pointer and the data-byte counter.

<<SPI: quad input data phase>>=
if (quad_in_phase) begin
   qin_phase <= ~qin_phase;
   if (qin_phase == 1'b0) begin
      nibble_buf <= io_d_in;
   end else begin
      addr_low    <= addr_low + 4'd1;
      quad_in_cnt <= quad_in_cnt + 20'd1;
   end
end
@

The byte-boundary arm runs on every eighth rise. It bumps the
display-side `byte_cnt`, advances the saturating `phase_cnt` (so
the eighth-and-beyond byte of a long transfer keeps matching the
catch-all `> 4` arms in the dispatch), and dispatches into the
opcode-specific arm.

<<SPI: byte boundary actions>>=
if (byte_done) begin
   byte_cnt  <= byte_cnt  + 16'd1;
   if (phase_cnt != 3'd7) phase_cnt <= phase_cnt + 3'd1;
   <<SPI: byte boundary opcode dispatch>>
end
@

The opcode dispatch handles, in order: byte 0 of any frame
(latch opcode, load any single-cycle response constant); the
0x9F JEDEC ID continuation bytes; 0x03 Normal Read (capture the
low byte of the 24-bit address on phase 3 and load the first
response byte directly from `byte_captured`, preloading
`data_byte` with the next pattern value; subsequent bytes
present `data_byte` and post-increment); 0x0B Fast Read (latch
the address LSB on phase 3 into `data_byte`; phase 4 boundary
loads the first data byte from `data_byte` and post-increments
because the dummy byte sits between the address phase and the
first response byte); 0x02 Page Program (latch RAM-buffer
address, increment under WEL gating); 0x32 Quad Page Program
(only the RAM-buffer address latch lives here; the data-phase
write is the quad-input chunk above); 0x6B Quad Output Read
(latch the address LSB into `data_byte` as the pattern seed that
`quad_start` copies into `quad_data_byte` after the dummy byte);
and 0x5A
SFDP Read (latch the low 7 bits of the 24-bit address into
`sfdp_idx` on byte 3, then on byte 4 onwards present
`sfdp_rom[sfdp_idx]` as the next response byte and
post-increment `sfdp_idx` so the catch-all arm streams the
table out sequentially; bytes 4 and >4 mirror the 0x0B
fast-read cadence because the dummy byte advances the same
way).

The `data_byte` register holds the running pattern value. Only
the address LSB matters for the pattern start (the high two
address bytes are accepted but unused since the pattern is
mod-256). For 0x03 the response data starts in the same byte
slot that latches the address LSB --- shift_out on that
boundary takes `byte_captured` directly, and `data_byte` is
preloaded to `byte_captured + 1` so that subsequent boundaries
see the next pattern value already sitting in the register. For
0x0B the dummy byte gives one extra slot, so the first response
byte is loaded from `data_byte` on the phase 4 boundary.

<<SPI: byte boundary opcode dispatch>>=
if (phase_cnt == 3'd0) begin
   opcode <= byte_captured;
   if (byte_captured == 8'h9F) shift_out <= 8'h20;
   else if (byte_captured == 8'h05) shift_out <= {6'b0, wel_s, 1'b0};
end else if (phase_cnt == 3'd1 && opcode == 8'h9F) begin
   shift_out <= 8'h20;
end else if (phase_cnt == 3'd2 && opcode == 8'h9F) begin
   shift_out <= 8'h14;
end else if (opcode == 8'h03 && phase_cnt == 3'd3) begin
   shift_out <= byte_captured;
   data_byte <= byte_captured + 8'd1;
end else if (opcode == 8'h03 && phase_cnt > 3'd3) begin
   shift_out <= data_byte;
end else if (opcode == 8'h0B && phase_cnt == 3'd3) begin
   data_byte <= byte_captured;
end else if (opcode == 8'h0B && phase_cnt >= 3'd4) begin
   shift_out <= data_byte;
end else if (opcode == 8'h02 && phase_cnt == 3'd3) begin
   addr_low <= new_low;
end else if (opcode == 8'h02 && phase_cnt > 3'd3 && wel) begin
   addr_low <= addr_low + 4'd1;
end else if (opcode == 8'h32 && phase_cnt == 3'd3) begin
   addr_low <= new_low;
end else if (opcode == 8'h6B && phase_cnt == 3'd3) begin
   data_byte <= byte_captured;
end else if (opcode == 8'h5A && phase_cnt == 3'd3) begin
   sfdp_idx <= byte_captured[6:0];
end else if (opcode == 8'h5A && phase_cnt >= 3'd4) begin
   shift_out <= sfdp_rd;
   sfdp_idx  <= sfdp_idx + 7'd1;
end
@

`wel` is set in the fclk domain on the cs-rise pulse; the RAM
write-enable is sclk-domain. A direct combinational reference
into the sclk-domain write would create a long unconstrained
path into the RAM block. `wel_s` mirrors `wel` through one sclk
flop so nextpnr can close timing on a single same-cycle path.

<<SPI: shift engine WEL synchroniser>>=
reg wel_s;
initial wel_s = 0;
always @(posedge sclk or posedge cs_async_rst) begin
   if (cs_async_rst) wel_s <= 1'b0;
   else      wel_s <= wel;
end
@

The shift engine no longer owns any RAM ports. The chunk
remains in the structure for documentation and to keep the
shift-engine block diagram intact; tangling produces no Verilog.

<<SPI: shift engine RAM ports>>=
@

The 128-byte SFDP (Serial Flash Discoverable Parameters, JESD216)
ROM answers the 0x5A opcode. The Linux m25p80 driver issues 0x5A
to confirm the device's published capabilities --- erase opcode,
density, fast-read modes --- before exposing the flash to the
filesystem layer. The ROM has three regions: an 8-byte SFDP
header at offset 0x00, a single 8-byte parameter header (BFPT,
Basic Flash Parameter Table) at offset 0x08, and the BFPT itself
at offset 0x30. Bytes between are 0xFF padding (matching erased
flash). The 7-bit `sfdp_idx` indexes the table; addresses above
0x7F wrap because the verifier reads from offsets 0x000, 0x100,
0x200, 0x300 and picks whichever 256-byte slice carries the
`SFDP` signature, so wrap is acceptable for the high-offset
reads as long as offset 0x000 returns the correct table.

The header at 0x00..0x07 is the JESD216 magic `'S','F','D','P'`,
SFDP minor/major rev (0x06/0x01 = JESD216B), NPH (0 = one
parameter header follows), and one 0xFF reserved byte.

The parameter header at 0x08..0x0F identifies its parameter
table as JEDEC BFPT by ID = 0x0000 (split across the LSB at
0x08 and the MSB at 0x0F per JESD216). Length = 16 dwords
satisfies the m25p80 sanity check that BFPT is large enough to
hold the QER (Quad Enable Requirements) field at dword 15. The
24-bit BFPT pointer is 0x000030 (LSB-first across bytes 0x0C-0x0E).

The BFPT at 0x30..0x6F is little-endian 32-bit dwords. DW1
(0x30..0x33) encodes erase support: bits[1:0]=01 (4 KB erase
supported), bits[15:8]=0x20 (4 KB erase opcode), bit 22 set
(1-1-4 fast read supported), with reserved-1 bits filled. DW2
(0x34..0x37) is the density field; per JESD216 with MSB=0 the
encoding is N+1 bits, so `N = 0x007FFFFF = 8388607` advertises
8 Mbit (= 1 MB), matching the JEDEC-ID continuation 0x14
(2^20 bytes). DW9 (0x50..0x53) lists sector erase types: type
1 is 4 KB at opcode 0x20, type 2 is 64 KB at opcode 0xD8.
DW15 (0x68..0x6B) carries the QER (Quad Enable Requirements)
field in bits[22:20]. We declare QER = 0 (no QE bit, Micron-
style) since this emulator never enters quad mode; byte 0x6A
must therefore present bits[6:4] = 000 with the surrounding
reserved bits left as 1, giving 0x8F. Without this the m25p80
driver reads QER = 7 from the all-ones padding and rejects the
device. All other unused dwords are 0xFF (reserved).

The ROM uses an `initial begin` block: explicit byte
assignments for the meaningful header/BFPT bytes, and `for`
loops for the 0xFF-fill regions. yosys infers this as
distributed LUT RAM because the read port is asynchronous.

<<SPI: SFDP ROM>>=
reg [7:0] sfdp_rom [0:127];
integer   _sfdp_i;
initial begin
   for (_sfdp_i = 0; _sfdp_i < 128; _sfdp_i = _sfdp_i + 1)
      sfdp_rom[_sfdp_i] = 8'hFF;

   sfdp_rom[7'h00] = 8'h53;
   sfdp_rom[7'h01] = 8'h46;
   sfdp_rom[7'h02] = 8'h44;
   sfdp_rom[7'h03] = 8'h50;
   sfdp_rom[7'h04] = 8'h06;
   sfdp_rom[7'h05] = 8'h01;
   sfdp_rom[7'h06] = 8'h00;
   sfdp_rom[7'h07] = 8'hFF;

   sfdp_rom[7'h08] = 8'h00;
   sfdp_rom[7'h09] = 8'h06;
   sfdp_rom[7'h0A] = 8'h01;
   sfdp_rom[7'h0B] = 8'h10;
   sfdp_rom[7'h0C] = 8'h30;
   sfdp_rom[7'h0D] = 8'h00;
   sfdp_rom[7'h0E] = 8'h00;
   sfdp_rom[7'h0F] = 8'hFF;

   sfdp_rom[7'h30] = 8'hFD;
   sfdp_rom[7'h31] = 8'h20;
   sfdp_rom[7'h32] = 8'hC0;
   sfdp_rom[7'h33] = 8'hFF;

   sfdp_rom[7'h34] = 8'hFF;
   sfdp_rom[7'h35] = 8'hFF;
   sfdp_rom[7'h36] = 8'h7F;
   sfdp_rom[7'h37] = 8'h00;

   sfdp_rom[7'h50] = 8'h0C;
   sfdp_rom[7'h51] = 8'h20;
   sfdp_rom[7'h52] = 8'h10;
   sfdp_rom[7'h53] = 8'hD8;

   sfdp_rom[7'h6A] = 8'h8F;
end
wire [7:0] sfdp_rd = sfdp_rom[sfdp_idx];
@

MISO output is the high bit of `shift_out` driven into the `io[1]`
pad through the IO drivers chunk. `shift_out` itself is registered on
`posedge sclk`, and the fabric `io_pad_out` presenter captures it on
the following `negedge sclk`, matching mode-0 output timing before
the unregistered pad drives the pin.
@

Write Enable Latch (WEL). With the streaming pattern source in
place there is no page-buffer storage; this block reduces to
the WEL flop and the `cs_n` CDC chain that the rest of the
fclk-domain logic shares. WEL is updated in the fclk domain on
the CS-rise pulse: set on a 1-byte 0x06 (WREN) frame, cleared
on a 1-byte 0x04 (WRDI) frame, and cleared again as a side
effect of any 0x02 / 0x32 program frame.

The status register exposed by 0x05 (RDSR) is synthesised from
this latch alone: bit 0 is WIP (write-in-progress) and is hard-
wired to 0 because we do not model program timing, bit 1 is WEL,
and bits 7:2 are reserved zeros. The shift engine loads this byte
into `shift_out` on the opcode boundary using the sclk-domain
mirror `wel_s` so the read path stays inside one clock domain.

The CS-rise pulse is generated by two-flop synchronising `cs_n` into
the fclk domain and detecting its rising edge. By the time the
pulse fires, the sclk-domain `opcode` and `byte_cnt` are stable (no
more sclk edges arrive until the next CS-fall), so reading them
from the fclk domain on this single pulse is safe.

The sclk-domain reset arm is driven by `cs_async_rst`, an fclk
flop with an asynchronous raw-`cs_n` fall release and a delayed
synchronized reassertion on CS rise. This lets each new transaction
leave reset immediately when the master asserts CS, while preserving
the delayed CS-rise clear that gives the fclk snapshot block a full
cycle to copy the completed frame before the sclk-domain source
flops are cleared. Verilator's `SYNCASYNCNET` warning is waived
locally around this block because that mixed use of `cs_n` is the
point of the circuit: raw fall is the reset-release path, while
the sampled chain owns CS-rise detection and reset reassertion.

<<SPI: page buffer and WEL>>=
<<SPI: page buffer storage>>
<<SPI: cs_n CDC chain>>
<<SPI: WEL update>>
@

<<SPI: page buffer storage>>=
reg wel;
initial begin
   wel = 0;
end
@

<<SPI: cs_n CDC chain>>=
/* verilator lint_off SYNCASYNCNET */
reg [1:0] cs_sync;
initial cs_sync = 2'b11;
always @(posedge clk) cs_sync <= {cs_sync[0], cs_n};
wire cs_s     = cs_sync[1];
reg  cs_s_d;
initial cs_s_d = 1'b1;
always @(posedge clk) cs_s_d <= cs_s;
wire cs_rise_pulse = !cs_s_d && cs_s;

reg cs_async_rst;
initial cs_async_rst = 1'b1;
always @(posedge clk or negedge cs_n) begin
   if (!cs_n)
      cs_async_rst <= 1'b0;
   else
      cs_async_rst <= cs_s_d;
end
/* verilator lint_on SYNCASYNCNET */
@

<<SPI: WEL update>>=
always @(posedge clk) begin
   if (frame_done) begin
      if (snap_op == 8'h06 && snap_byte_cnt == 8'd1)
         wel <= 1'b1;
      else if (snap_op == 8'h04 && snap_byte_cnt == 8'd1)
         wel <= 1'b0;
      else if (snap_op == 8'h02 || snap_op == 8'h32)
         wel <= 1'b0;
   end
end
@

For 0x6B Quad Output Read the FPGA drives all four IO pins during
the data phase at one nibble per SCLK cycle. The real 0x6B stream
drives the UPPER and LOWER nibbles of each logical byte in pad-visible
order, matching the STM32MP1 QUADSPI byte assembly seen on hardware.
Diagnostic opcodes 0x6C, 0x6D, 0x6E, and 0x6F keep their existing
pad-visible nibble order so their lane
and phase probes remain comparable across builds. Each nibble is presented on the
preceding SCLK falling edge so the master samples stable data on the
rising edge (mode 0). Each data byte therefore takes 2 SCLK cycles =
2 `bit_cnt` increments = a quarter of a single-lane byte period;
`byte_cnt` still counts single-lane SCLK-bytes, so sixteen quad data
bytes show up as four `byte_cnt` increments in the printer's
`bytes=` field.

The engine partitions into state, the data-phase qualifiers, the
posedge-precomputed pad source, and the fabric negedge presenter.
For 0x6B, `quad_start` loads the captured address-low pattern seed
into `quad_data_byte` and emits the upper nibble first. The shared
byte-oriented quad cadence then emits the lower nibble, advances the
byte, and emits the next upper nibble. This keeps 0x6B independent
from the single-lane `data_byte` update path while preserving the
diagnostic opcodes' original nibble cadence.

<<SPI: quad output engine>>=
<<SPI: quad output state>>
<<SPI: quad output qualifiers>>
<<SPI: quad output pad source>>
<<SPI: quad output pad presenter>>
@

`quad_next_nibble` is the precomputed nibble the pad data mux drives
on `io[3:0]` during the quad data phase. `quad_data_byte` and
`quad_hi_next` track the byte-oriented 0x6B stream and diagnostic
streams such as 0x6E.
`quad_diag_idx` advances the 0x6C and
0x6D diagnostic nibble sequences.

<<SPI: quad output state>>=
reg [3:0] quad_next_nibble;
reg [7:0] quad_data_byte;
reg       quad_data_drive_r;
reg       quad_hi_next;
reg       quad_active;
reg [3:0] quad_diag_idx;
wire [3:0] quad_diag6d_nibble =
   quad_diag_idx[0] ? (4'h6 + {1'b0, quad_diag_idx[3:1]}) : 4'h0;
initial begin
   quad_next_nibble   = 0;
   quad_data_byte     = 0;
   quad_data_drive_r  = 0;
   quad_hi_next        = 0;
   quad_active         = 0;
   quad_diag_idx       = 0;
end

function automatic [3:0] quad_onehot(input [1:0] idx);
   case (idx)
      2'd0: quad_onehot = 4'h1;
      2'd1: quad_onehot = 4'h2;
      2'd2: quad_onehot = 4'h4;
      default: quad_onehot = 4'h8;
   endcase
endfunction
@

`quad_data` is high during the quad output data phase only --- after
the opcode, three address bytes, and dummy byte (five
single-lane SCLK-bytes). `quad_start` fires on the byte boundary
that ends the 0x6B/0x6C/0x6D/0x6E/0x6F dummy byte; that one-cycle transition primes
the first pad nibble, sets `quad_active`, and enables the quad
output drivers before the first data-phase negedge. The latched
active qualifier then stays high for the rest of the selected
frame instead of being re-derived from the saturating byte-phase
counter. `quad_data_byte_inc` and `quad_hold_byte_inc` advance the
byte-oriented diagnostic streams.

<<SPI: quad output qualifiers>>=
wire       quad_data     = quad_active;
wire       quad_start    = byte_done && phase_cnt == 3'd4
                        && (opcode == 8'h6B || opcode == 8'h6C
                         || opcode == 8'h6D || opcode == 8'h6E
                         || opcode == 8'h6F);
wire [7:0] quad_data_byte_seed = data_byte;
wire [7:0] quad_data_byte_inc = quad_data_byte + 8'd1;
wire [7:0] quad_hold_byte_inc = (quad_data_byte == 8'hFF)
                              ? 8'h00 : (quad_data_byte + 8'h11);
@

The pad source is fed by a posedge precompute inside the shift engine.
The precompute produces `quad_next_nibble` --- the 4-bit quad value
driven directly on `io[3:0]` during the quad data phase. Lane 1 selects
either that quad bit or the serial `shift_out[7]` bit; outside quad data,
the serial response path still uses the falling-edge presenter.

The precompute uses explicit phase flops to select upper-vs-lower
nibbles. The dummy-to-data `quad_start` edge stages the captured
address-low seed and prepares the first pad nibble. For 0x6B that
first nibble is the seed upper nibble; diagnostics keep their
established pad-visible cadence.

<<SPI: quad output pad source>>=
wire [3:0] io_pad_src = {
   quad_next_nibble[3],
   quad_next_nibble[2],
   quad_data_drive ? quad_next_nibble[1] : shift_out[7],
   quad_next_nibble[0]
};
@

The falling-edge presenter is the registered launch point for all
slave-driven data. It captures the posedge-precomputed `io_pad_src`
for single-lane and quad responses. `io_pad_selected` names the
registered source connected to the pad data wires, so the debug
sampler and physical output mux stay consistent.

<<SPI: quad output pad presenter>>=
reg [3:0] io_pad_out;
initial begin
   io_pad_out = 0;
end
always @(negedge sclk or posedge cs_async_rst) begin
   if (cs_async_rst) begin
      io_pad_out <= 0;
   end else begin
      io_pad_out <= io_pad_src;
   end
end
@

For 0x32 Quad Page Program the master drives all four IO pins
during the data phase; the FPGA samples `io[3:0]` on each SCLK
rising edge (mode 0 sample point) and pairs two rises into one
byte (IO3..IO0 → upper nibble first, then lower). The sampling,
RAM write, and pointer/count advance all live inside the shift
engine's `posedge sclk` process to avoid multiple drivers on
`addr_low` and the page buffer; the state registers
(`quad_in_cnt`, `nibble_buf`, `qin_phase`) are likewise declared
in the shift-engine state chunk above.

`quad_in_cnt` counts data bytes received during a 0x32 frame; the
end-of-frame latch uses it to render the printer's `bytes=` field
in byte-equivalents (1 opcode + 3 addr + N data bytes), ignoring
how many SCLK cycles were physically used.

This chunk is intentionally empty: the structure-only reference
above holds the prose, and there is nothing left to tangle.

<<SPI: quad input engine>>=
@

Four explicit iCE40 `SB_IO` drivers, one per lane. Only `io[1]`
carries a useful single-lane response (`shift_out[7]` gated by
`resp_window`); the other lanes stay Hi-Z until a quad-output
data phase, when all four outputs drive the precomputed lane value
through the pads. The drivers
split into the two qualifiers, the per-lane data and OE wires,
the pad cells, and the testbench-visible aggregate views.

Each lane gets its own named OE wire. Bundling all four lanes
through a single OE expression lets yosys collapse `io[0]`,
`io[2]`, and `io[3]` onto one shared `$_TBUF_` in an intermediate
pass, dropping OE on the collapsed lanes in the placed bitstream.
Instantiating the four pad cells directly prevents that sharing
and makes the lane-to-package-pin mapping explicit.

<<SPI: IO drivers>>=
<<SPI: IO drive qualifiers>>
<<SPI: IO per-lane OE and data>>
<<SPI: IO pad drivers>>
<<SPI: IO testbench views>>
@

`resp_window` is the single-lane MISO window on `io[1]` for any
opcode that returns a serial response. `quad_data_drive` covers
the quad-output data phase across all four lanes. Both are gated
on the raw `cs_n` pin so the bus snaps to Hi-Z the instant CS
rises, before the fclk-domain synchroniser of `cs_n` has even
settled.

<<SPI: IO drive qualifiers>>=
wire resp_window = (!cs_n)
                && ( ((opcode == 8'h9F) && (phase_cnt >= 3'd1) && (phase_cnt <= 3'd3))
                  || ((opcode == 8'h05) && (phase_cnt == 3'd1))
                  || ((opcode == 8'h03) && (phase_cnt >= 3'd4))
                  || ((opcode == 8'h0B) && (phase_cnt >= 3'd5))
                  || ((opcode == 8'h5A) && (phase_cnt >= 3'd5)) );
wire quad_data_drive = (!cs_n) && quad_data_drive_r;
wire [3:0] io_pad_selected = io_pad_out;
@

Per-lane OE wires. `io_oe_1` is the only lane that aggregates
both the single-lane response window and the quad data phase;
the other three lanes drive only during quad data.

<<SPI: IO per-lane OE and data>>=
wire io_oe_0    = quad_data_drive;
wire io_oe_1    = quad_data_drive | resp_window;
wire io_oe_2    = quad_data_drive;
wire io_oe_3    = quad_data_drive;
wire io_d_out_0 = io_pad_selected[0];
wire io_d_out_1 = io_pad_selected[1];
wire io_d_out_2 = io_pad_selected[2];
wire io_d_out_3 = io_pad_selected[3];
@

Each lane instantiates its own bidirectional pad cell. The output side
uses the unregistered iCE40 bidirectional form (`PIN_TYPE = 6'b101001`);
the data mux above always selects the registered presenter. The input
side routes through `D_IN_0` so all MOSI and quad-write sampling sees
the same pad view that the hardware uses.

<<SPI: IO pad drivers>>=
wire io_d_in_0;
wire io_d_in_1;
wire io_d_in_2;
wire io_d_in_3;
SB_IO #(
   .PIN_TYPE(6'b101001)
) io0_iob (
   .PACKAGE_PIN(io[0]),
   .OUTPUT_ENABLE(io_oe_0),
   .D_OUT_0(io_d_out_0),
   .D_IN_0(io_d_in_0)
);
SB_IO #(
   .PIN_TYPE(6'b101001)
) io1_iob (
   .PACKAGE_PIN(io[1]),
   .OUTPUT_ENABLE(io_oe_1),
   .D_OUT_0(io_d_out_1),
   .D_IN_0(io_d_in_1)
);
SB_IO #(
   .PIN_TYPE(6'b101001)
) io2_iob (
   .PACKAGE_PIN(io[2]),
   .OUTPUT_ENABLE(io_oe_2),
   .D_OUT_0(io_d_out_2),
   .D_IN_0(io_d_in_2)
);
SB_IO #(
   .PIN_TYPE(6'b101001)
) io3_iob (
   .PACKAGE_PIN(io[3]),
   .OUTPUT_ENABLE(io_oe_3),
   .D_OUT_0(io_d_out_3),
   .D_IN_0(io_d_in_3)
);
@

`io_oe` packs the per-lane OE wires into a 4-bit bus for the
testbench to probe. `io_d_in` is the combinational input view
reported by the four pad cells.

<<SPI: IO testbench views>>=
wire [3:0] io_oe   = {io_oe_3, io_oe_2, io_oe_1, io_oe_0};
wire [3:0] io_d_in = {io_d_in_3, io_d_in_2, io_d_in_1, io_d_in_0};
@

MOSI CRC-32 (IEEE-802.3 reflected, poly 0xEDB88320, init 0xFFFFFFFF,
final XOR 0xFFFFFFFF). Updated byte-serially: on each sclk_rise that
completes a byte (bit_cnt == 7), the just-captured byte
`{shift_in[6:0], mosi_s}` is folded into `crc_reg` in one cycle
through a combinational 8-step unrolled byte update, gated by the
`master_driven_byte` qualifier. The CRC scope covers only bytes the
master actually drove on MOSI (opcode + address + dummy + write-data
bytes); bytes clocked during a read-data phase (where MOSI floats)
are excluded. `cs_fall` resets the register to the init value. At
`cs_rise` the final value is snapped and XOR'd with 0xFFFFFFFF; the
frame-latch block below consumes the snapshot.

The qualifier decision for the just-completed byte at pre-increment
`byte_cnt == N` is:
- N == 0 (opcode): always master-driven;
- opcode == 0x9F or 0x05: only N == 0 (data phase is slave-driven);
- opcode == 0x03: N <= 3 (opcode + 3 addr); N >= 4 excluded;
- opcode == 0x0B: N <= 3 (opcode + 3 addr); dummy byte N==4 and
  data N >= 5 excluded (the master tri-states MOSI during dummy);
- opcode == 0x5A: N <= 3 (opcode + 3 addr); dummy byte N==4 and
  data N >= 5 excluded (same cadence as 0x0B);
- opcode == 0x6B / 0x6C / 0x6D / 0x6E / 0x6F: N <= 3 (opcode + 3 addr); dummy N==4 and quad
  data N >= 5 excluded (master tri-states all four IO pins during
  dummy and quad data);
- everything else (0x02, 0x06, 0xBB, unknown): all bytes master-driven.

The CRC engine partitions into the register and the
combinational fold functions, the master-driven-byte qualifier
that limits the CRC scope, the 0x32 quad-input alternate fold
hook, and the sclk-domain update process.

<<SPI: MOSI CRC-32>>=
<<SPI: CRC register and fold functions>>
<<SPI: master-driven qualifier>>
<<SPI: quad-input byte-done qualifier>>
<<SPI: CRC update process>>
@

`crc_reg` lives in the sclk domain alongside the rest of the
capture state. `crc32_step` does one bit; `crc32_byte` unrolls
eight LSB-first steps so the byte fold completes in a single
cycle. The `+ 4'd9` style offset is unnecessary here because
`crc32_byte` simply chains eight `crc32_step` calls in order.

<<SPI: CRC register and fold functions>>=
reg [31:0] crc_reg;
initial crc_reg = 32'hFFFFFFFF;

function automatic [31:0] crc32_step(input [31:0] c, input bit_in);
   crc32_step = {1'b0, c[31:1]}
              ^ ((c[0] ^ bit_in) ? 32'hEDB88320 : 32'h00000000);
endfunction

function automatic [31:0] crc32_byte(input [31:0] c, input [7:0] b);
   crc32_byte = crc32_step(crc32_step(crc32_step(crc32_step(
                  crc32_step(crc32_step(crc32_step(crc32_step(
                     c, b[0]), b[1]), b[2]), b[3]),
                              b[4]), b[5]), b[6]), b[7]);
endfunction
@

The CRC scope covers only bytes the master actually drove on
MOSI (opcode + address + dummy + write-data); bytes clocked
during a read-data phase, where MOSI floats, are excluded. The
qualifier reads `phase_cnt` and `opcode` combinationally; on
the boundary that captures the opcode (`phase_cnt == 0`) we
short-circuit to "always driven" because `opcode` is being
updated on the same edge.

<<SPI: master-driven qualifier>>=
wire master_driven_byte =
     (phase_cnt == 3'd0)                               ? 1'b1 :
     (opcode == 8'h9F || opcode == 8'h05)              ? 1'b0 :
     (opcode == 8'h03)                                 ? (phase_cnt <= 3'd3) :
     (opcode == 8'h0B)                                 ? (phase_cnt <= 3'd3) :
     (opcode == 8'h5A)                                 ? (phase_cnt <= 3'd3) :
     (opcode == 8'h6B)                                 ? (phase_cnt <= 3'd3) :
     (opcode == 8'h6C)                                 ? (phase_cnt <= 3'd3) :
     (opcode == 8'h6D)                                 ? (phase_cnt <= 3'd3) :
     (opcode == 8'h6E)                                 ? (phase_cnt <= 3'd3) :
     (opcode == 8'h6F)                                 ? (phase_cnt <= 3'd3) :
     (opcode == 8'h32)                                 ? (phase_cnt <= 3'd3) :
                                                         1'b1;
@

For 0x32 the data-phase bytes arrive across `io[3:0]` rather
than serially on MOSI, so `shift_in` does not hold the
completed byte. Instead the CRC update folds the reconstructed
`{nibble_buf, io[3:0]}` at the instant the lower nibble lands
(`qin_phase == 1` on a quad-input rise).

<<SPI: quad-input byte-done qualifier>>=
wire quad_in_byte_done = quad_in_phase && (qin_phase == 1'b1);
@

`cs_async_rst` clears the register to the IEEE init value. On every
single-lane byte boundary the captured byte is folded under the
master-driven qualifier; on every 0x32 quad-input lower-nibble
rise the reconstructed byte is folded instead.

<<SPI: CRC update process>>=
always @(posedge sclk or posedge cs_async_rst) begin
   if (cs_async_rst) begin
      crc_reg <= 32'hFFFFFFFF;
   end else if ((bit_cnt == 3'd7) && master_driven_byte) begin
      crc_reg <= crc32_byte(crc_reg, {shift_in[6:0], io_d_in[0]});
   end else if (quad_in_byte_done) begin
      crc_reg <= crc32_byte(crc_reg, {nibble_buf, io_d_in});
   end
end
@

End-of-frame latch. On the CS rising edge, snap `opcode`,
`byte_cnt`, and the finalised MOSI CRC (XOR'd with 0xFFFFFFFF) into
registers the printer FSM consumes, and pulse `frame_done` for one
cycle.

The latch splits into a precomputed display-byte-count, the
sclk-domain snapshot register triggered by the `cs_n` rising
edge itself, the fclk-domain `frame_done` pulse for the printer,
and the snapshot aliases consumed by the page-buffer/WEL block.

<<SPI: end-of-frame latch>>=
<<SPI: end-of-frame display byte count>>
<<SPI: end-of-frame snapshot>>
<<SPI: end-of-frame done pulse>>
<<SPI: end-of-frame snapshot aliases>>
@

`frame_cnt_pre` collapses `byte_cnt` and `quad_in_cnt` into the
single value the printer wants to display, so the snapshot
carries one count instead of two (saving roughly twenty flops).
For 0x32, the displayed count is "1 opcode + 3 addr + N data"
in byte-equivalents.

<<SPI: end-of-frame display byte count>>=
wire [15:0] frame_cnt_pre_full = (opcode == 8'h32)
                               ? (16'd4 + {4'd0, quad_in_cnt[11:0]})
                               : byte_cnt;
wire [7:0]  frame_cnt_pre        = frame_cnt_pre_full[7:0];
wire [7:0]  unused_frame_cnt_hi  = frame_cnt_pre_full[15:8];
@

The snapshot is clocked synchronously by `clk` and fires on the
`cs_rise_pulse` --- the fclk-domain rising-edge detector for
`cs_s`. Raw `cs_n` falling releases `cs_async_rst` immediately
for the next frame, but CS-rise reassertion still follows the
delayed synchronized path. When `cs_rise_pulse` is asserted (the
fclk window between `cs_s` rising and `cs_s_d` catching up), the
upcoming fclk edge both snapshots the source registers *and*
loads `cs_async_rst <= cs_s_d`. Because that load samples the
pre-edge `cs_s_d = 0`, the asynchronous clear of the source flops
does not fire on the snapshot edge; it fires one fclk later. The
snapshot therefore observes the source flops in their post-frame
state, before any clear propagates.

The earlier formulation used `always @(posedge cs_async_rst)` and
relied on Verilog non-blocking semantics to sample the source
registers "before" the asynchronous clear propagated. In silicon
the snapshot register and the async-clear inputs of the source
flops both observed the same `cs_async_rst` edge, racing each
other through whichever global network nextpnr picked for the
signal; depending on routing skew the snapshot captured the
post-clear (zero) value, leaving `frame_op` permanently 0 and
no useful printer output ever reached the UART pin. The
synchronous formulation below removes that race.

<<SPI: end-of-frame snapshot>>=
reg [7:0]  frame_op;
reg [7:0]  frame_cnt;
reg [31:0] frame_crc_raw;
initial begin
   frame_op       = 0;
   frame_cnt      = 0;
   frame_crc_raw  = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
end

always @(posedge clk) begin
   if (cs_rise_pulse) begin
      frame_op      <= opcode;
      frame_cnt     <= frame_cnt_pre[7:0];
      frame_crc_raw <= crc_reg;
   end
end
@

`frame_done` is a one-cycle pulse in the fclk domain produced
from the synchronised CS-rise. `frame_crc` is the finalised
(XOR'd) CRC, materialised combinationally from `frame_crc_raw`
so the snapshot register stays narrow.

<<SPI: end-of-frame done pulse>>=
wire [31:0] frame_crc = frame_crc_raw ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF;
reg         frame_done;
initial frame_done = 0;
always @(posedge clk) frame_done <= cs_rise_pulse;
@

The page-buffer/WEL block in the fclk domain distinguishes 0x06
(set WEL) and 0x04 (clear WEL via WRDI) from 0x02 / 0x32 (clear
WEL as a program-frame side effect) by reading the snapshot
opcode and byte count. Aliasing them under `snap_*` names keeps
that block's intent obvious without a second copy of the
register.

<<SPI: end-of-frame snapshot aliases>>=
wire [7:0]  snap_op       = frame_op;
wire [7:0]  snap_byte_cnt = frame_cnt;
@

The printer FSM emits exactly one line per frame, of the form:

    op=<hh> bytes=<dd> mosi_crc=<hhhhhhhh>\r\n

Two-digit hex opcode, two-digit decimal byte count (correct for
any transfer up to 99 SCLK-bytes; longer transfers roll over in
the displayed field but the underlying counter and CRC engine
do not), fixed-width 8-digit hex CRC. The FSM partitions into
state encoding, register declarations and helpers, and the per-
character `case` arms grouped by output region.

<<SPI: UART printer FSM>>=
<<Printer: state encoding>>
<<Printer: registers>>
<<Printer: helpers>>
<<Printer: process>>
@

Each character of the output line gets its own state. The FSM
walks them top-to-bottom: load on `frame_done`, then the literal
`"op="`, two opcode hex digits, `" bytes="`, an optional tens
digit + units digit, `" mosi_crc="`, eight hex CRC digits, CR,
LF.

<<Printer: state encoding>>=
localparam P_IDLE = 6'd0;
localparam P_O    = 6'd1;
localparam P_P    = 6'd2;
localparam P_EQ1  = 6'd3;
localparam P_HH   = 6'd4;
localparam P_HL   = 6'd5;
localparam P_SP   = 6'd6;
localparam P_B    = 6'd7;
localparam P_Y    = 6'd8;
localparam P_T    = 6'd9;
localparam P_E    = 6'd10;
localparam P_S    = 6'd11;
localparam P_EQ2  = 6'd12;
localparam P_D1   = 6'd13;
localparam P_D0   = 6'd14;
localparam P_SP2  = 6'd15;
localparam P_MM   = 6'd16;
localparam P_MO   = 6'd17;
localparam P_MS   = 6'd18;
localparam P_MI   = 6'd19;
localparam P_MU   = 6'd20;
localparam P_MC   = 6'd21;
localparam P_MR   = 6'd22;
localparam P_MC2  = 6'd23;
localparam P_EQ3  = 6'd24;
localparam P_C7   = 6'd25;
localparam P_C6   = 6'd26;
localparam P_C5   = 6'd27;
localparam P_C4   = 6'd28;
localparam P_C3   = 6'd29;
localparam P_C2   = 6'd30;
localparam P_C1   = 6'd31;
localparam P_C0   = 6'd32;
localparam P_CR   = 6'd33;
localparam P_LF   = 6'd34;
@

`p_op`, `p_cnt`, and `p_crc` latch the snapshot at the moment
`frame_done` fires so the printer's slow walk does not race a
new frame's snapshot if SPI is already running again.

<<Printer: registers>>=
reg [5:0]  pstate;
reg [7:0]  p_op;
reg [7:0]  p_cnt;
reg [31:0] p_crc;
reg        tx_start;
reg  [7:0] tx_data;
wire       tx_busy;

initial begin
   pstate   = P_IDLE;
   p_op     = 0;
   p_cnt    = 0;
   p_crc    = 0;
   tx_start = 0;
   tx_data  = 0;
end
@

`hexchar` maps a nibble to lowercase ASCII hex; `d1`/`d0` split
the byte count into tens and units for the `bytes=` field.

<<Printer: helpers>>=
function [7:0] hexchar(input [3:0] n);
   hexchar = (n < 4'd10) ? (8'h30 + {4'h0, n})
                          : (8'h61 + {4'h0, n} - 8'd10);
endfunction
wire [3:0] d1, d0;
wire [3:0] unused_d1_hi, unused_d0_hi;
assign {unused_d1_hi, d1} = p_cnt / 8'd10;
assign {unused_d0_hi, d0} = p_cnt % 8'd10;
@

The process body is a single `case (pstate)` whose arms split
top-to-bottom into the load step, the literal-prefix walks, and
the data-hex walks. `tx_start` defaults low every cycle so any
arm wanting to issue a byte just reassigns it; the
`!tx_busy && !tx_start` gate matches the `uart_tx` handshake
contract documented in the UART chapter.

<<Printer: process>>=
always @(posedge clk) begin
   tx_start <= 1'b0;
   case (pstate)
      <<Printer: arm idle and load>>
      <<Printer: arms for "op=" prefix>>
      <<Printer: arms for opcode hex>>
      <<Printer: arms for " bytes=" prefix>>
      <<Printer: arms for byte count digits>>
      <<Printer: arms for " mosi_crc=" prefix>>
      <<Printer: arms for CRC hex digits>>
      <<Printer: arms for CR/LF tail>>
      default: pstate <= P_IDLE;
   endcase
end
@

<<Printer: arm idle and load>>=
P_IDLE: if (frame_done) begin
           p_op   <= frame_op;
           p_cnt  <= frame_cnt;
           p_crc  <= frame_crc;
           pstate <= P_O;
        end
@

<<Printer: arms for "op=" prefix>>=
P_O:   if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "o"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_P;   end
P_P:   if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "p"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_EQ1; end
P_EQ1: if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "="; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_HH;  end
@

<<Printer: arms for opcode hex>>=
P_HH:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(p_op[7:4]); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_HL; end
P_HL:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(p_op[3:0]); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_SP; end
@

<<Printer: arms for " bytes=" prefix>>=
P_SP:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= " "; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_B;   end
P_B:   if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "b"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_Y;   end
P_Y:   if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "y"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_T;   end
P_T:   if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "t"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_E;   end
P_E:   if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "e"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_S;   end
P_S:   if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "s"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_EQ2; end
P_EQ2: if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "="; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_D1;  end
@

`P_D1` skips the tens digit when the byte count is a single
digit so `bytes=4` reads naturally instead of `bytes=04`.

<<Printer: arms for byte count digits>>=
P_D1:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin
           if (d1 != 0) begin
              tx_data <= hexchar(d1); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_D0;
           end else pstate <= P_D0;
        end
P_D0:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(d0); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_SP2; end
@

<<Printer: arms for " mosi_crc=" prefix>>=
P_SP2: if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= " "; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_MM;  end
P_MM:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "m"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_MO;  end
P_MO:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "o"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_MS;  end
P_MS:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "s"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_MI;  end
P_MI:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "i"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_MU;  end
P_MU:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "_"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_MC;  end
P_MC:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "c"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_MR;  end
P_MR:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "r"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_MC2; end
P_MC2: if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "c"; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_EQ3; end
P_EQ3: if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= "="; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_C7;  end
@

<<Printer: arms for CRC hex digits>>=
P_C7:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(p_crc[31:28]); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_C6; end
P_C6:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(p_crc[27:24]); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_C5; end
P_C5:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(p_crc[23:20]); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_C4; end
P_C4:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(p_crc[19:16]); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_C3; end
P_C3:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(p_crc[15:12]); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_C2; end
P_C2:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(p_crc[11: 8]); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_C1; end
P_C1:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(p_crc[ 7: 4]); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_C0; end
P_C0:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= hexchar(p_crc[ 3: 0]); tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_CR; end
@

<<Printer: arms for CR/LF tail>>=
P_CR:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= 8'h0d; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_LF;   end
P_LF:  if (!tx_busy && !tx_start) begin tx_data <= 8'h0a; tx_start <= 1; pstate <= P_IDLE; end
@

The UART transmitter is the one defined verbatim in the UART chapter.
115200 baud @ 12 MHz => CLKS_PER_BIT = 104.

<<SPI: uart_tx instance>>=
uart_tx #(.CLKS_PER_BIT(104)) u_tx (
   .clk  (clk),
   .start(tx_start),
   .data (tx_data),
   .tx   (tx),
   .busy (tx_busy)
);
@

=== Pin map

iCEstick pin numbers for the already-wired rig. The 12 MHz
oscillator is on pin 21; CS / SCLK / MOSI / MISO are on the Pmod
pins used by the existing MP135 wiring; UART TX is pin 8 back to the
FT2232H channel B.

<<qspi.pcf>>=
set_io clk     21
set_io tx       8
set_io cs_n    56
set_io sclk    45
set_io io[0]   47
set_io io[1]   44
set_io io[2]   60
set_io io[3]   48
@

=== Build fragment

Two Verilog sources tangle into the build: `qspi.v` for the slave
itself and `uart_tx.v` reused verbatim from the UART chapter.
The simulator also needs a local `SB_IO` model for the falling-edge
fabric launch path and unregistered bidirectional pads used by qspi;
synthesis uses yosys' built-in iCE40 primitive instead.

<<qspi.mk>>=
QSPI_VS := verilog/qspi.v verilog/uart_tx.v
QSPI_SIM_LIB := build/qspi/SB_IO.v

build/qspi/qspi.json: $(QSPI_VS) | build/qspi
	cd build/qspi && yosys -q -p "read_verilog ../../verilog/qspi.v ../../verilog/uart_tx.v; synth_ice40 -top qspi -json qspi.json"

build/qspi/SB_IO.v: src/qspi.nw | build/qspi
	cd build/qspi && tangle SB_IO.v < ../../$<

build/qspi/sim: tb/tb_qspi.sv $(QSPI_VS) verilog/uart_rx.v $(QSPI_SIM_LIB) | build/qspi
	cd build/qspi && verilator --Mdir obj_dir -Wall --binary --top-module tb_qspi ../../tb/tb_qspi.sv ../../verilog/qspi.v ../../verilog/uart_tx.v ../../verilog/uart_rx.v SB_IO.v
	cd build/qspi && obj_dir/Vtb_qspi
	@touch $@

bitstream: build/qspi/qspi.bin
sim: build/qspi/sim
@

=== `SB_IO` simulation model

The qspi slave uses unregistered bidirectional pads
(`PIN_TYPE = 6'b101001`) with the falling-edge launch register in
fabric. This model is intentionally scoped to that configuration: it
drives `D_OUT_0` directly when `OUTPUT_ENABLE` is asserted, otherwise
releases the bus, and `D_IN_0` always mirrors the package pin.

<<SB_IO.v>>=
module SB_IO #(
      parameter [5:0] PIN_TYPE    = 6'b000000,
      parameter [0:0] NEG_TRIGGER = 1'b0
   ) (
      inout  PACKAGE_PIN,
      input  OUTPUT_ENABLE,
      input  D_OUT_0,
      output D_IN_0
   );
   initial begin
      if (!(PIN_TYPE === 6'b101001 && NEG_TRIGGER === 1'b0)) begin
         $display("ERROR qspi SB_IO sim model only supports PIN_TYPE=101001 NEG_TRIGGER=0, got %b %b",
                  PIN_TYPE, NEG_TRIGGER);
         $finish;
      end
   end

   assign PACKAGE_PIN = OUTPUT_ENABLE ? D_OUT_0 : 1'bz;
   assign D_IN_0 = PACKAGE_PIN;
endmodule
@

=== Testbench

The testbench drives two SPI frames on the DUT. First, a 0x9F (JEDEC
read id) frame that clocks out three extra bytes on MISO while MOSI
idles at zero (total 4 bytes); second, a one-byte 0xBB frame. A
sniffer `uart_rx` decodes the DUT's TX line into a small circular
queue; the stimulus reads back the two log lines and asserts their
contents match `op=9f bytes=4` and `op=bb bytes=1`.

<<tb_qspi.sv>>=
`timescale 1ns/1ps

module tb_qspi;
   localparam CLKS_PER_BIT = 104;

   reg clk;
   initial clk = 0;
   always #5 clk <= ~clk;

   reg       cs_n, sclk;
   wire      tx;

   // Master-side tri-state drivers for the four IO pins. Each lane
   // is driven by the TB only when its `oe` bit is set; otherwise
   // the TB leaves the line as 1'bz so the DUT can drive it. The
   // DUT exposes the lines as `inout [3:0] io` with its own
   // tri-state enables per lane.
   reg  [3:0] tb_io_out;
   reg  [3:0] tb_io_oe;
   wire [3:0] io;
   genvar gi;
   generate
      for (gi = 0; gi < 4; gi = gi + 1) begin : tb_io_drivers
         assign io[gi] = tb_io_oe[gi] ? tb_io_out[gi] : 1'bz;
      end
   endgenerate

   // Convenience handles for the TB's single-lane view. `mosi` is
   // the TB-driven line into the DUT (io[0] when oe is set); `miso`
   // is the DUT's single-lane response line (io[1] read back).
   wire miso = io[1];

   qspi dut (
      .clk (clk),
      .cs_n(cs_n),
      .sclk(sclk),
      .io  (io),
      .tx  (tx)
   );

   initial begin
      cs_n     = 1;
      sclk     = 0;
      tb_io_out = 4'b0000;
      tb_io_oe  = 4'b0000;
   end

   // Shorthand: a single-lane spi_byte sets TB oe to drive only
   // io[0] (MOSI). A quad sample routine drops all oe so the DUT
   // can drive all four IO pins during a 0x6B data phase.
   task automatic set_mosi_drive();
      begin
         tb_io_oe = 4'b0001;
      end
   endtask
   task automatic release_io();
      begin
         tb_io_oe  = 4'b0000;
         tb_io_out = 4'b0000;
      end
   endtask

   wire       sniff_ready;
   wire [7:0] sniff_data;
   uart_rx #(.CLKS_PER_BIT(CLKS_PER_BIT)) sniffer (
      .clk  (clk),
      .rx   (tx),
      .ready(sniff_ready),
      .data (sniff_data)
   );

   reg [7:0] rx_queue [0:255];
   reg [7:0] rx_head, rx_tail;
   initial begin rx_head = 0; rx_tail = 0; end
   always @(posedge clk) begin
      if (sniff_ready) begin
         rx_queue[rx_head] <= sniff_data;
         rx_head <= rx_head + 1;
      end
   end

   string     line;
   // SCLK timing knobs. The legacy slow path uses #60/#120/#60 per
   // bit (240 ns => ~4.17 MHz). Tests at the end push these much
   // smaller to verify the redesigned sclk-domain capture path runs
   // cleanly at 50 MHz and beyond.
   integer t_q  = 60;   // quarter-bit setup window
   integer t_h  = 120;  // SCLK high duration
   reg [31:0] oracle_crc;
   function automatic [31:0] crc32_step(input [31:0] c, input bit_in);
      crc32_step = (c >> 1)
                 ^ ((c[0] ^ bit_in) ? 32'hEDB88320 : 32'h00000000);
   endfunction
   function automatic [31:0] crc32_byte(input [31:0] c, input [7:0] b);
      crc32_byte = crc32_step(crc32_step(crc32_step(crc32_step(
                     crc32_step(crc32_step(crc32_step(crc32_step(
                        c, b[0]), b[1]), b[2]), b[3]),
                                 b[4]), b[5]), b[6]), b[7]);
   endfunction

   // Drive one SPI byte, MSB first, and capture MISO MSB-first on
   // SCLK rising edges (mode 0 -- master samples on rise). Each half
   // period is 12 FPGA clk cycles (clk = 10 ns, half-period = 120 ns
   // => ~4.17 MHz SCLK), slow enough to exercise the real multi-cycle
   // gap between sclk_rise and sclk_fall on the DUT. The `driven`
   // flag gates `oracle_crc` accumulation: pass 1 for opcode /
   // address / dummy / write-data bytes (master-driven on MOSI), 0
   // for bytes clocked only to read MISO from the slave.
   task automatic spi_byte(input [7:0] b, input driven, output [7:0] got);
      integer i;
      begin
         tb_io_oe = 4'b0001; // drive only io[0] = MOSI
         got = 8'h00;
         for (i = 7; i >= 0; i = i - 1) begin
            tb_io_out[0] = b[i];
            #(t_q);
            sclk = 1;
            got[i] = miso;
            #(t_h);
            sclk = 0;
            #(t_q);
         end
         if (driven) oracle_crc = crc32_byte(oracle_crc, b);
      end
   endtask

   // Send-only variant used wherever the slave's MISO byte is
   // ignored (opcode and address bytes of write/program frames,
   // dummy clocks ahead of slave-driven phases).
   task automatic spi_send(input [7:0] b, input driven);
      integer i;
      begin
         tb_io_oe = 4'b0001;
         for (i = 7; i >= 0; i = i - 1) begin
            tb_io_out[0] = b[i];
            #(t_q);
            sclk = 1;
            #(t_h);
            sclk = 0;
            #(t_q);
         end
         if (driven) oracle_crc = crc32_byte(oracle_crc, b);
      end
   endtask

   // 0x6B dummy byte: master tri-states all four IO lines for 8
   // SCLK cycles and does not sample anything useful on MISO.
   task automatic spi_dummy_quad();
      integer i;
      begin
         tb_io_oe  = 4'b0000;
         tb_io_out = 4'b0000;
         for (i = 0; i < 8; i = i + 1) begin
            #(t_q);
            sclk = 1;
            #(t_h);
            sclk = 0;
            #(t_q);
         end
      end
   endtask

   // Quad data byte: master tri-states all four IO lines and
   // samples IO[3:0] on each SCLK rise. Two rises per data byte.
   // Diagnostics and 0x6B drive UPPER nibble on the first negedge
   // and LOWER on the second.
   //
   // Sampling cadence matches a real QSPI master and also asserts
   // the bus does not change while SCLK is high. Each nibble is read
   // immediately after the rising edge and again at the end of the
   // high pulse; the two samples must match, and the end sample is
   // what the byte assembler consumes.
   task automatic spi_quad_data_byte_ordered(input low_first, output [7:0] got);
      reg [3:0] first_start, first_nib;
      reg [3:0] second_start, second_nib;
      begin
         tb_io_oe  = 4'b0000;
         tb_io_out = 4'b0000;
         #(t_q);
         sclk = 1;
         #1;
         first_start = io[3:0];
         if (t_h > 1) #(t_h - 1);
         first_nib = io[3:0];
         if (first_start !== first_nib)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: quad first nibble changed while SCLK high: start=%b end=%b",
                   first_start, first_nib);
         sclk = 0;
         #(t_q);
         sclk = 1;
         #1;
         second_start = io[3:0];
         if (t_h > 1) #(t_h - 1);
         second_nib = io[3:0];
         if (second_start !== second_nib)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: quad second nibble changed while SCLK high: start=%b end=%b",
                   second_start, second_nib);
         sclk = 0;
         #(t_q);
         got = low_first ? {second_nib, first_nib} : {first_nib, second_nib};
      end
   endtask

   task automatic spi_quad_data_byte(output [7:0] got);
      begin
         spi_quad_data_byte_ordered(1'b0, got);
      end
   endtask

   task automatic spi_quad_data_byte_6b(output [7:0] got);
      begin
         spi_quad_data_byte_ordered(1'b0, got);
      end
   endtask

   // Master-side quad data write (0x32 data phase). Master drives
   // all four IO pins at one nibble per SCLK cycle using the same
   // JEDEC nibble mapping as the quad-output path. Also folds the
   // byte into `oracle_crc` (master-driven).
   task automatic spi_quad_write_byte(input [7:0] b);
      begin
         tb_io_oe  = 4'b1111;
         tb_io_out = b[7:4];   // upper nibble: IO3=b7 .. IO0=b4
         #(t_q);
         sclk = 1;
         #(t_h);
         sclk = 0;
         #(t_q);
         tb_io_out = b[3:0];   // lower nibble: IO3=b3 .. IO0=b0
         #(t_q);  // wait; second half of the previous cycle already
         sclk = 1;
         #(t_h);
         sclk = 0;
         #(t_q);
         oracle_crc = crc32_byte(oracle_crc, b);
      end
   endtask

   // Format and compare a captured log line against the step-9
   // schema: `op=<hh> bytes=<dd> mosi_crc=<8hex>`. The byte count
   // is displayed modulo 100 by the DUT's 2-digit printer; for the
   // streaming tests we pass the value already taken modulo 100 so
   // the expected string lines up with what the DUT emits.
   // Parse and compare a captured log line against an expected
   // `prefix` and finalised CRC (prefix should be e.g. "op=9f
   // bytes=4"; the CRC is appended as " mosi_crc=hhhhhhhh").
   task automatic expect_line(input string prefix, input [31:0] crc);
      string expected;
      begin
         expected = $sformatf("%s mosi_crc=%08h", prefix, crc);
         recv_line(line);
         $display("captured: %s", line);
         if (line != expected)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: want '%s' got '%s'", expected, line);
      end
   endtask

   // Pop bytes from the sniffer queue until an LF, returning the
   // line (CR stripped) as a string.
   task automatic recv_line(output string s);
      reg [7:0] b;
      reg       done;
      begin
         s = "";
         done = 0;
         while (!done) begin
            while (rx_head === rx_tail) @(posedge clk);
            b = rx_queue[rx_tail];
            rx_tail = rx_tail + 1;
            if (b == 8'h0a) done = 1;
            else if (b != 8'h0d) s = {s, string'(b)};
         end
      end
   endtask

   reg [7:0] got0, got1, got2, got3;

   initial begin
      repeat (50) @(posedge clk);

      // Frame 1: 0x9F + 3 dummy bytes (total 4 bytes).
      oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      @(posedge clk);
      // Before CS falls: all OEs must be low.
      if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
         $fatal(1, "FAIL: pre-frame io_oe = %b, want 0000", dut.io_oe);
      cs_n = 0;
      #200;
      // Opcode phase (master driving io[0]): all OEs still low.
      if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
         $fatal(1, "FAIL: opcode-phase io_oe = %b, want 0000", dut.io_oe);
      spi_byte(8'h9F, 1'b1, got0);   // opcode (master-driven)
      // After opcode boundary the slave drives io[1] (single-lane MISO)
      // for the data phase. Other lanes remain Hi-Z.
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got1);   // read phase (slave-driven)
      if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0010)
         $fatal(1, "FAIL: 9F data-phase io_oe = %b, want 0010", dut.io_oe);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got2);
      if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0010)
         $fatal(1, "FAIL: 9F data-phase io_oe = %b, want 0010", dut.io_oe);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got3);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      #50;
      if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
         $fatal(1, "FAIL: post-CS io_oe = %b, want 0000", dut.io_oe);

      $display("MISO trace: byte0=%02h byte1=%02h byte2=%02h byte3=%02h",
               got0, got1, got2, got3);
      if (got1 !== 8'h20) $fatal(1, "FAIL: MISO byte1 = %02h", got1);
      if (got2 !== 8'h20) $fatal(1, "FAIL: MISO byte2 = %02h", got2);
      if (got3 !== 8'h14) $fatal(1, "FAIL: MISO byte3 = %02h", got3);
      expect_line("op=9f bytes=4", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0;
      #200;
      spi_byte(8'hBB, 1'b1, got0);
      #200 cs_n = 1;

      $display("MISO trace (non-9F): byte0=%02h", got0);
      if (got0 !== 8'h00) $fatal(1, "FAIL: MISO on non-9F = %02h", got0);
      expect_line("op=bb bytes=1", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0;
      #200;
      spi_byte(8'h05, 1'b1, got0);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got1);
      #200 cs_n = 1;

      $display("MISO trace (05): byte0=%02h byte1=%02h", got0, got1);
      if (got1 !== 8'h00) $fatal(1, "FAIL: RDSR MISO byte1 = %02h", got1);
      expect_line("op=05 bytes=2", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);

      // Frame 3b: WREN, then RDSR -- expect SR bit1 (WEL) = 1.
      oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0; #200;
      spi_byte(8'h06, 1'b1, got0);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      expect_line("op=06 bytes=1", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0; #200;
      spi_byte(8'h05, 1'b1, got0);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got1);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      $display("MISO trace (05 post-WREN): byte0=%02h byte1=%02h", got0, got1);
      if (got1 !== 8'h02)
         $fatal(1, "FAIL: RDSR after WREN expected 0x02, got %02h", got1);
      expect_line("op=05 bytes=2", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);

      // Frame 3c: WRDI, then RDSR -- expect SR bit1 (WEL) = 0.
      oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0; #200;
      spi_byte(8'h04, 1'b1, got0);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      expect_line("op=04 bytes=1", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0; #200;
      spi_byte(8'h05, 1'b1, got0);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got1);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      $display("MISO trace (05 post-WRDI): byte0=%02h byte1=%02h", got0, got1);
      if (got1 !== 8'h00)
         $fatal(1, "FAIL: RDSR after WRDI expected 0x00, got %02h", got1);
      expect_line("op=05 bytes=2", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);

      // Slave drives 16 pattern bytes starting at addr 0: 0,1,...,15.
      begin : frame4
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0;
         #200;
         spi_send(8'h03, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
            end
         #200 cs_n = 1;

         $write("MISO trace (03 pattern at addr 0):");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 03 pattern data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=03 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 5: 0x02 without WREN. Slave drives nothing.
      oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0; #200;
      spi_byte(8'h02, 1'b1, got0);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b1, got0);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b1, got0);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b1, got0);
      spi_byte(8'hAA, 1'b1, got0);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      expect_line("op=02 bytes=5", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      // Frame 6: 0x03 read at addr 0 -- pattern reads are
      // independent of the page buffer, so this just confirms the
      // pattern source is unaffected by a prior no-WEL 0x02 frame.
      begin : frame6
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h03, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got0);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         $display("MISO trace (03 after no-WEL 02): %02h", got0);
         if (got0 !== 8'h00)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 03 pattern at addr 0: got %02h, want 00", got0);
         expect_line("op=03 bytes=5", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 7: WREN.
      oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0; #200;
      spi_byte(8'h06, 1'b1, got0);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      expect_line("op=06 bytes=1", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      begin : frame8
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h02, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            spi_send(8'h50 + k[7:0], 1'b1);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         expect_line("op=02 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 9: 0x03 read at addr 0x000010 -- expect pattern
      // 0x10..0x1F. Confirms the address LSB is captured into
      // the pattern counter.
      begin : frame9
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h03, 1'b1);  // opcode
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);  // addr [23:16]
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);  // addr [15:8]
         spi_send(8'h10, 1'b1);  // addr [7:0]
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
            end
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         $write("MISO trace (03 pattern at addr 0x10):");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== (8'h10 + k[7:0]))
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 03 pattern at 0x10 data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], 8'h10 + k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=03 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 10: 0x0B Fast Read -- slave drives 16 data bytes.
      begin : frame10
         reg [7:0] got_dummy;
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h0B, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h80, 1'b1);  // addr LSB = 0x80
         spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_dummy);  // not slave-driven
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
            end
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         $display("MISO during 0x0B dummy byte: %02h", got_dummy);
         if (got_dummy !== 8'h00)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 0x0B dummy MISO = %02h, want 00", got_dummy);
         $write("MISO trace (0B pattern at addr 0x80):");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== (8'h80 + k[7:0]))
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 0B pattern data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], 8'h80 + k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=0b bytes=21", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 11: 0x6B Quad Output Read -- slave drives 16 quad
      // pattern bytes starting at addr 0xFE so the wrap from 0xFF
      // back to 0x00 is exercised on the quad path.
      begin : frame11
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);

         release_io();
         if (tb_io_oe !== 4'b0000)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: TB did not release IO before 0x6B frame");

         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h6B, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'hFE, 1'b1);  // addr LSB = 0xFE -- exercises wrap
         // Probe the DUT's per-lane output enable: must be 0 during
         // the dummy byte (master tri-states all four lanes), and
         // must turn on for all four lanes once the data phase
         // begins. Step-13 hardware bug: only 3 of 4 lanes actually
         // drove during the data phase, so the master saw the bus
         // idle state (0xDD) instead of slave data.
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6B io_oe asserted during dummy: %b",
                   dut.io_oe);
         spi_dummy_quad();
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b1111)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6B io_oe must drive all 4 lanes after dummy, got %b",
                   dut.io_oe);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            spi_quad_data_byte_6b(got_arr[k]);
            if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b1111)
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6B io_oe dropped during data byte %0d: %b",
                      k, dut.io_oe);
            end
         #200 cs_n = 1;

         #100;
         if (io !== 4'bzzzz)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: DUT did not release IO after CS rise, io=%b", io);
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6B io_oe must drop after CS rise: %b",
                   dut.io_oe);

         $write("QUAD trace (6B pattern at addr 0xFE):");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== (8'hFE + k[7:0]))
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6B pattern data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], 8'hFE + k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=6b bytes=9", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 11b: 0x6C Quad Output Read -- same framing as 0x6B
      // but emits one-hot nibbles 1,2,4,8,... for lane/phase
      // diagnostics. Upper-first byte assembly yields 12 48 ...
      begin : frame11b
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         reg [7:0] want;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);

         release_io();
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h6C, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6C io_oe asserted during dummy: %b",
                   dut.io_oe);
         spi_dummy_quad();
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b1111)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6C io_oe must drive all 4 lanes after dummy, got %b",
                   dut.io_oe);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            spi_quad_data_byte(got_arr[k]);
            if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b1111)
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6C io_oe dropped during data byte %0d: %b",
                      k, dut.io_oe);
         end
         #200 cs_n = 1;

         #100;
         if (io !== 4'bzzzz)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: DUT did not release IO after 6C CS rise, io=%b", io);
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6C io_oe must drop after CS rise: %b",
                   dut.io_oe);

         $write("QUAD trace (6C one-hot nibbles):");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            want = k[0] ? 8'h48 : 8'h12;
            if (got_arr[k] !== want)
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6C one-hot data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], want);
         end
         expect_line("op=6c bytes=9", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 11c: 0x6D Quad Output Read -- same framing as 0x6B
      // but emits byte diagnostics 06..0d repeatedly.
      begin : frame11c
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         reg [7:0] want;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);

         release_io();
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h6D, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6D io_oe asserted during dummy: %b",
                   dut.io_oe);
         spi_dummy_quad();
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b1111)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6D io_oe must drive all 4 lanes after dummy, got %b",
                   dut.io_oe);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            spi_quad_data_byte(got_arr[k]);
            if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b1111)
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6D io_oe dropped during data byte %0d: %b",
                      k, dut.io_oe);
         end
         #200 cs_n = 1;

         #100;
         if (io !== 4'bzzzz)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: DUT did not release IO after 6D CS rise, io=%b", io);
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6D io_oe must drop after CS rise: %b",
                   dut.io_oe);

         $write("QUAD trace (6D byte sequence):");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            want = 8'h06 + {5'b0, k[2:0]};
            if (got_arr[k] !== want)
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6D sequence data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], want);
         end
         expect_line("op=6d bytes=9", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 12: 0x32 WITHOUT prior 0x06 -- WEL is clear, so the
      // quad-input write must be ignored. Send addr=0 + 16 data
      // bytes 0xC0..0xCF in quad. `bytes=` field is in byte-
      // equivalents: 1 + 3 + 16 = 20.
      begin : frame12
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h32, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            spi_quad_write_byte(8'hC0 + k[7:0]);
         release_io();
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         expect_line("op=32 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 13: 0x03 readback after no-WEL 32 -- pattern source
      // is independent of the page buffer, so the response must
      // be the addr-0 pattern (0x00..0x0F) regardless of what the
      // (rejected) write tried to do.
      begin : frame13
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h03, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
            end
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         $write("MISO trace (03 after no-WEL 32):");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 03 pattern data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=03 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 14: WREN.
      oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0; #200;
      spi_byte(8'h06, 1'b1, got0);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      expect_line("op=06 bytes=1", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      begin : frame15
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h32, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            // 0x32 is a quad WRITE: master drives all four lanes;
            // the slave must NOT drive any io_oe during this phase.
            if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 32 data byte %0d io_oe=%b, want 0000",
                      k, dut.io_oe);
            spi_quad_write_byte(8'hC0 + k[7:0]);
         end
         release_io();
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         expect_line("op=32 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 16: 0x03 readback after WEL+quad-32 -- pattern at
      // addr 0 is 0x00..0x0F, independent of any prior writes.
      begin : frame16
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h03, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
            end
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         $write("MISO trace (03 after quad-32, pattern):");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 03 pattern data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=03 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 16b: 0x6B quad-output readback at addr 0 -- expect
      // pattern 0x00..0x0F. Nibble-alignment regression: the
      // 0x6B now intentionally drives `{byte_N_upper, byte_N_lower}`
      // on the pads so the testbench assembles the logical byte
      // expected by the master.
      begin : frame16b
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc      = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         release_io();
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h6B, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6B/CF pre-dummy io_oe=%b", dut.io_oe);
         spi_dummy_quad();
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b1111)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6B/CF data-phase io_oe=%b, want 1111",
                   dut.io_oe);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) begin
            spi_quad_data_byte_6b(got_arr[k]);
            if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b1111)
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6B/CF io_oe dropped during byte %0d: %b",
                      k, dut.io_oe);
         end
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         #50;
         if (dut.io_oe !== 4'b0000)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6B/CF post-CS io_oe=%b", dut.io_oe);
         $write("QUAD trace (6B pattern at addr 0):");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: 6B pattern data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=6b bytes=9", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frames 17--22: high-rate stress at 50 MHz SCLK to verify
      // the redesigned sclk-domain capture path. The fclk is 100
      // MHz (10 ns) in this TB; setting t_q = t_h = 10 ns gives a
      // 30 ns SCLK period (one quarter setup + one half + one
      // quarter low) ~= 33 MHz. Drop t_q/t_h to 5 ns each to push
      // SCLK to 50 MHz.
      t_q = 5;
      t_h = 10;

      // Frame 17: 0x9F at high rate. Confirms shift-out load on
      // byte boundary and miso_out negedge tap both meet timing.
      oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0; #200;
      spi_byte(8'h9F, 1'b1, got0);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got1);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got2);
      spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got3);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      $display("HS 9F: %02h %02h %02h %02h", got0, got1, got2, got3);
      if (got1 !== 8'h20 || got2 !== 8'h20 || got3 !== 8'h14)
         $fatal(1, "FAIL: high-rate 9F miso = %02h %02h %02h",
                got1, got2, got3);
      expect_line("op=9f bytes=4", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);

      // Frame 18: WREN at high rate.
      oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0; #200;
      spi_byte(8'h06, 1'b1, got0);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      expect_line("op=06 bytes=1", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);

      // Frame 19: 0x02 PP at high rate, write 0xA0..0xAF.
      begin : hs_pp
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h02, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            spi_send(8'hA0 + k[7:0], 1'b1);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         expect_line("op=02 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 20: 0x03 readback at high rate, addr=0 pattern.
      begin : hs_rd
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h03, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         $write("HS 03 rd pattern:");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: high-rate 03 data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=03 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 20b: long single-lane 0x03 read (40 data bytes)
      // starting at addr LSB 0xF0 so the 8-bit pattern counter
      // wraps from 0xFF back to 0x00 mid-frame. This is the
      // headline streaming integrity check: every emitted byte
      // must equal `(0xF0 + k) mod 256` so any framing or CDC
      // glitch in the long stream is caught byte-by-byte.
      begin : hs_rd_long
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:39];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h03, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'hF0, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 40; k = k + 1)
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         $write("HS 03 long pattern from 0xF0:");
         for (k = 0; k < 40; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 40; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== (8'hF0 + k[7:0]))
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: long-03 pattern data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], 8'hF0 + k[7:0]);
         // Total SCLK-bytes = 1 opcode + 3 addr + 40 data = 44.
         // Printer shows modulo 100 => "44".
         expect_line("op=03 bytes=44", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 21: WREN, then 0x32 quad PP at high rate, write
      // 0xE0..0xEF, then 0x03 readback.
      oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
      repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
      @(posedge clk);
      cs_n = 0; #200;
      spi_byte(8'h06, 1'b1, got0);
      #200 cs_n = 1;
      expect_line("op=06 bytes=1", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);

      begin : hs_qpp
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h32, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            spi_quad_write_byte(8'hE0 + k[7:0]);
         release_io();
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         expect_line("op=32 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 22: 0x03 readback at high rate, addr=0 pattern.
      begin : hs_qrd
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h03, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         $write("HS 03 pattern after quad-32:");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: high-rate 03 data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=03 bytes=20", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 23: 0x6B Quad Output Read at high rate, addr LSB
      // 0x40 -- pattern starts at 0x40, increments through 0x4F.
      begin : hs_qor
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:15];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         release_io();
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h6B, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h40, 1'b1);
         spi_dummy_quad();
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            spi_quad_data_byte_6b(got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         $write("HS 6B pattern from 0x40:");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         for (k = 0; k < 16; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== (8'h40 + k[7:0]))
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: high-rate 6B data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], 8'h40 + k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=6b bytes=9", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 24: 0x5A SFDP Read at offset 0. Drive opcode + 3
      // address bytes (0x00 0x00 0x00) + 1 dummy byte, then read
      // 8 SFDP bytes. The first 4 bytes must be the JESD216
      // signature `S`,`F`,`D`,`P` (0x53 0x46 0x44 0x50).
      begin : sfdp_rd
         reg [7:0] got_dummy;
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:7];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h5A, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_dummy);
         for (k = 0; k < 8; k = k + 1)
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         $display("SFDP dummy byte: %02h", got_dummy);
         if (got_dummy !== 8'h00)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: 0x5A dummy MISO = %02h, want 00", got_dummy);
         $write("SFDP trace (5A):");
         for (k = 0; k < 8; k = k + 1) $write(" %02h", got_arr[k]);
         $display("");
         if (got_arr[0] !== 8'h53 || got_arr[1] !== 8'h46
          || got_arr[2] !== 8'h44 || got_arr[3] !== 8'h50)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: SFDP signature = %02h %02h %02h %02h",
                   got_arr[0], got_arr[1], got_arr[2], got_arr[3]);
         expect_line("op=5a bytes=13", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Streaming pattern stress -- mirrors the MP135 host's 1 MiB
      // streaming reads. The pattern source emits `addr[7:0]` and
      // wraps every 256 bytes; these frames check that the wrap
      // remains glitch-free across many mod-256 cycles, on both
      // single-lane (0x03 / 0x0B) and quad-output (0x6B) paths,
      // before hardware comes online. Reuses the high-rate t_q/t_h
      // already in effect (t_q=5, t_h=10 -> ~50 MHz SCLK) so the
      // long bursts complete in tens of microseconds each.
      //
      // The DUT's printer snapshots `byte_cnt` truncated to 8 bits;
      // the displayed value is `byte_cnt mod 256` rendered as
      // 1- or 2-digit decimal. Verified against existing assertions:
      // frame20b above sends 1+3+40 = 44 single-lane bytes and
      // expects "op=03 bytes=44".

      // Frame 25: 0x0B Fast Read, 1024 data bytes from addr 0x000.
      // Total byte_cnt = 1+3+1+1024 = 1029; 1029 mod 256 = 5.
      begin : stream_0b_1k
         reg [7:0] got_dummy;
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:1023];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h0B, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);  // addr LSB = 0x00
         spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_dummy);
         for (k = 0; k < 1024; k = k + 1)
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         if (got_dummy !== 8'h00)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: stream-0B-1k dummy MISO = %02h, want 00", got_dummy);
         for (k = 0; k < 1024; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: stream-0B-1k data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=0b bytes=5", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 26: 0x0B Fast Read, 256 data bytes from addr 0x0FE.
      // Pattern: 0xFE, 0xFF, 0x00, 0x01, ..., 0xFD.
      // Total byte_cnt = 1+3+1+256 = 261; 261 mod 256 = 5.
      begin : stream_0b_wrap
         reg [7:0] got_dummy;
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:255];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h0B, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'hFE, 1'b1);  // addr LSB = 0xFE -- wrap mid-frame
         spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_dummy);
         for (k = 0; k < 256; k = k + 1)
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         if (got_dummy !== 8'h00)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: stream-0B-wrap dummy MISO = %02h, want 00", got_dummy);
         for (k = 0; k < 256; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== (8'hFE + k[7:0]))
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: stream-0B-wrap data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], 8'hFE + k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=0b bytes=5", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 27: 0x6B Quad Output Read, 1024 data bytes from addr 0x000.
      // Each quad data byte = 2 SCLK rises = 0.25 byte_cnt; the dummy
      // contributes 1 (8 SCLK rises). Total byte_cnt = 1+3+1+1024/4
      // = 261; 261 mod 256 = 5.
      begin : stream_6b_1k
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:1023];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         release_io();
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h6B, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);  // addr LSB = 0x00
         spi_dummy_quad();
         for (k = 0; k < 1024; k = k + 1)
            spi_quad_data_byte_6b(got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         for (k = 0; k < 1024; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: stream-6B-1k data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=6b bytes=5", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 28: 0x6B Quad Output Read, 256 data bytes from addr 0x0FE.
      // Quad pattern wrap: 0xFE, 0xFF, 0x00, ..., 0xFD.
      // Total byte_cnt = 1+3+1+256/4 = 69 -> "bytes=69".
      begin : stream_6b_wrap
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:255];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         release_io();
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h6B, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'hFE, 1'b1);  // addr LSB = 0xFE -- wrap mid-frame
         spi_dummy_quad();
         for (k = 0; k < 256; k = k + 1)
            spi_quad_data_byte_6b(got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         for (k = 0; k < 256; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== (8'hFE + k[7:0]))
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: stream-6B-wrap data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], 8'hFE + k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=6b bytes=69", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 29: 0x03 Read, 1024 data bytes from addr 0x000. No
      // dummy byte for 0x03. Total byte_cnt = 1+3+1024 = 1028;
      // 1028 mod 256 = 4 -> "bytes=4".
      begin : stream_03_1k
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:1023];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h03, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         for (k = 0; k < 1024; k = k + 1)
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         for (k = 0; k < 1024; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: stream-03-1k data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         expect_line("op=03 bytes=4", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 30/31: ULTRA-high SCLK (~91 MHz) streaming stress on
      // both single-lane fast read and quad-output read. Mimics
      // the timing pressure that exposed the data_byte mux bug on
      // hardware: a 41 MHz silicon SCLK saw `data_byte` increment
      // twice between consecutive single-lane bytes because the
      // dispatch case-chain composed a deep adder+mux into the
      // pattern flop. Pulling the increment out of the chain into
      // its own gated assignment shortens the path; this frame
      // runs the resulting design at simulator's t_q = 3 ns,
      // t_h = 5 ns (period 11 ns => ~91 MHz), well into the
      // sclk-domain Fmax envelope.
      t_q = 3;
      t_h = 5;

      // Frame 30: 0x0B Fast Read, 256 data bytes from addr 0x000
      // at ~91 MHz SCLK. The deterministic pattern (k & 0xFF)
      // catches single-lane data_byte cadence faults that the
      // 50 MHz frames above run too slowly to provoke.
      begin : stream_0b_ultra
         reg [7:0] got_dummy;
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:255];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h0B, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_dummy);
         for (k = 0; k < 256; k = k + 1)
            spi_byte(8'h00, 1'b0, got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         if (got_dummy !== 8'h00)
            $fatal(1, "FAIL: stream-0B-ultra dummy MISO = %02h, want 00", got_dummy);
         for (k = 0; k < 256; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: stream-0B-ultra data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         // 1 + 3 + 1 + 256 = 261 bytes; printer renders mod 256 = 5.
         expect_line("op=0b bytes=5", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      // Frame 31: 0x6B Quad Output Read, 256 data bytes from addr 0
      // at ~91 MHz SCLK. The tightened spi_quad_data_byte sample
      // window (sample at end of high time, not at the rising
      // edge) makes any remaining slave-side cadence skew between
      // the negedge nibble drive and the master's sample show up
      // as a per-byte data error.
      begin : stream_6b_ultra
         reg [7:0] got_arr [0:255];
         integer   k;
         oracle_crc = 32'hFFFFFFFF;
         repeat (200) @(posedge clk);
         release_io();
         @(posedge clk);
         cs_n = 0; #200;
         spi_send(8'h6B, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_send(8'h00, 1'b1);
         spi_dummy_quad();
         for (k = 0; k < 256; k = k + 1)
            spi_quad_data_byte_6b(got_arr[k]);
         #200 cs_n = 1;
         for (k = 0; k < 256; k = k + 1)
            if (got_arr[k] !== k[7:0])
               $fatal(1, "FAIL: stream-6B-ultra data[%0d]=%02h want %02h",
                      k, got_arr[k], k[7:0]);
         // 1 + 3 + 1 + 256/4 = 69 bytes; mod 256 = 69.
         expect_line("op=6b bytes=69", oracle_crc ^ 32'hFFFFFFFF);
      end

      $display("PASS");
      $finish;
   end

   initial begin
      #60_000_000;
      $fatal(1, "timeout");
   end
endmodule
@

=== Hardware testing

==== Hardware Needed

- Lattice iCEstick (iCE40-HX1K, 12 MHz)
- USB-A extension cable or hub for the iCEstick
- An external SPI master wired to the Pmod pins matching the
  chapter's pin map (CS=56, SCLK=45, MOSI=`io[0]`=47, MISO=`io[1]`=44,
  `io[2]`=60, `io[3]`=48); the FT4222 referenced by the `dsp` plugin
  is the canonical master when its SPI lines are routed to the
  iCEstick rather than to the SHARC carrier's QSPI header

==== Test Setup

The iCEstick's FT2232H exposes the FPGA UART (115200, 8N1) on
which the slave prints one log line per completed SPI frame:
`op=<hh> bytes=<K> mosi_crc=<8hex>\r\n`. The CRC field is CRC-32
over the MOSI bytes of that frame.

==== Manual Test

Program the bitstream and open a 115200/8N1 terminal on the FPGA
UART. With nothing driving CS no UART line appears. Assert CS and
clock four bytes `9f 00 00 00` (single-lane, mode 0): the terminal
prints `op=9f bytes=4 mosi_crc=<hex>`. Drive a second frame of two
bytes `05 00`: the terminal prints `op=05 bytes=2 mosi_crc=<hex>`.
Equality of the CRC across runs of the same payload is the
trivial sanity check.

==== Automated Test

The standard rig in this repository wires the only available SPI
master (the FT4222 referenced by the `dsp` plugin) to the SHARC
carrier's QSPI header, not to the iCEstick. The automated test
therefore restricts itself to the path that does work without any
master-side wiring: program the bitstream and confirm the program
op completed cleanly. Frame-logging coverage is owned by the
simulation testbench above; the manual test is the route to
verify it on real silicon.

<<TEST.md>>=
```
fpga:program bin=@qspi.bin
```

- Check `test_serv` had no errors
@

The verifier has only the generic "no errors" predicate from the
shared library: the plan's only meaningful outcome is whether
`fpga:program` returned cleanly.

<<verify.py>>=
import os
import sys

sys.path.insert(0, os.path.join(
    os.path.dirname(os.path.abspath(__file__)), "..", "..", "lib"))
import verify_lib as v


DISPATCH = {
    "Check `test_serv` had no errors":
        v.check_no_errors,
}


if __name__ == "__main__":
    sys.exit(v.main(DISPATCH, sys.argv))
@

==== Test runner

`build/qspi/Makefile` is the entry point invoked from `cd build/qspi
&& make test`. It re-tangles the plan and the verifier from
`src/qspi.nw` so an edit to this chapter is picked up on the next
test run, then hands off to the shared `run_md.py` driver pointed at
by `$TEST_SERV`. The tangle recipes mirror the per-chapter rules in
the top Makefile but are reachable from inside the build directory
without invoking the parent.

<<Makefile>>=
NW := ../../src/qspi.nw

.PHONY: all test
all: TEST.md verify.py

test: all
	python3 $$TEST_SERV/run_md.py

TEST.md: $(NW)
	tangle TEST.md < $<

verify.py: $(NW)
	tangle verify.py < $<
@

=== Summary

The chapter's verification stack now mirrors the rest of the
project. The Verilator testbench drives every supported opcode
through the slave at simulation speed and on the high-rate
sclk/fclk decoupling path, asserting both the wire-side response
bytes and the per-frame UART log lines. Hardware testing loads
the bitstream onto a real iCEstick and confirms the program path
is clean; exercising the SPI side requires an external master and
is described as a manual procedure. `TEST.md` and `verify.py`
tangle out of this chapter so the plan and per-bullet check stay
attached to the prose that justifies them.
